0c06bc81ac5b4c8dffe2f02a55956d3c3a6e58ed.text:
Simulate a person using an LLM. Respond like a regular person. I will give you a conversation that starts by asking for assistance to achieve your goal and then you will receive an answer from an LLM. If you goal achieved, you should not respond. If not, you will write the person's next response based on both previous turns! Generate only the last human response.<br/><br/>You said this to an LLM: <br/><div style="
    background-color: #e6f7ff;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;">give me a nginx config to make nginx a proxy for https requests</div><br/><br/>LLM response:<br/><div style="
    background-color: #fff3e6;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Here is a sample nginx configuration to make nginx a proxy for HTTPS requests:</p>
<pre><code class="language-nginx"># HTTP server block to redirect all requests to HTTPS
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.com;
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

# HTTPS server block with SSL certificate and proxy settings
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name example.com;

    # SSL certificate
    ssl_certificate /path/to/example.com.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /path/to/example.com.key;

    # Proxy settings for HTTPS requests
    location / {
        proxy_pass https://backend.server.com;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;

        # Optional: disable SSL verification
        proxy_ssl_verify off;
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>In this configuration, all HTTP requests to example.com will be redirected to HTTPS. The HTTPS server block listens on port 443 and sets up SSL certificates using the specified paths. The <code>location /</code> directive forwards all requests to the upstream server at <code>https://backend.server.com</code>. The <code>proxy_set_header</code> directives pass along the original host name and client IP address to the upstream server. The last directive <code>proxy_ssl_verify off</code> is optional and can be used to disable SSL verification.</p></div>

